{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01T4s69p8TR4RoAjfiqvS4gz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. Now I have a complete picture. Let me set up the todo list and start implementing.\n\nKey plan:\n1. Install jsdom + @testing-library/react as devDependencies\n2. Write unit tests first (Step 1)\n3. Implement production code (Step 2)\n4. Run all checks\n\nImportant considerations from the biome config:\n- 2-space indentation\n- Biome linting with recommended rules + react/next domains\n\nFrom tsconfig: `\"jsx\": \"react-jsx\"` - good for React JSX transform.\n\n\nNow I'm breaking this down into concrete steps: first I'll install the test dependencies, then write tests for the chip components and the event explorer hook, and finally implement the production code for those components and the event table.\n\nI'm thinking through how MUI Chip renders in v9 — when it has an onClick handler, it becomes a button with `role=\"button\"` and `tabIndex={0}`, but without onClick it's just a plain div. For testing, I need to account for this difference when querying for the chip elements. I need to verify how MUI Popover renders in jsdom—it should appear in a portal at document.body, so the expanded JSON content will be findable with screen queries after clicking. For the JsonChip tests, I'm planning to check that the chip displays truncated key names rather than the full JSON, and then verify the \"No properties\" case for empty inputs.\n\nFor IdentityChip, I need to test that the resolved_id displays correctly and that the link points to the right encoded user path.\n\nI'm mocking Next.js Link to avoid router context issues in tests by replacing it with a simple anchor element. For the useEventExplorer hook tests, I need jsdom since the hook relies on `window.location.origin`, which defaults to `\"http://localhost\"` in that environment. I'll also need to mock the fetch function.\n\nFor the effect dependency, I'm considering whether to use an empty dependency array or include `fetchEvents` — since `fetchEvents` is memoized with `useCallback`, either approach works, but an empty array is simpler for the initial load.\n\nNow I'm thinking through how `setFilter` and `loadMore` will capture their dependencies...\n\n`setFilter` only needs `fetchEvents` since it resets the state directly, so it stays stable. But `loadMore` has to depend on `loading`, `hasMore`, `filter`, and `cursor` since it reads those values, which means it'll recreate whenever any of them change—that causes the EventTable to get a new `onLoadMore` prop and the IntersectionObserver to reconnect each time, but that's acceptable.\n\nActually, I realize `fetchEvents` uses `setEvents((prev) => ...)` to avoid capturing the events array, and it gets `filter` through the options parameter, so the closure is clean. The state setters are stable, so the design should work.\n\nNow I need to implement this and make sure I'm importing the MUI components correctly—the codebase uses individual imports like `from \"@mui/material/Table\"` rather than barrel imports.\n\nOne thing to watch: MUI v9's `Chip` component with `component={Link}` can cause TypeScript issues, so I'll wrap it with Next's Link component instead and apply the styling directly, which also makes testing easier since the link role will be on the outer element.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the DOM structure when Next.js Link wraps the Chip—the `<a>` tag becomes the parent with the href, and the Chip renders as a button-role div inside it, so `screen.getByRole(\"link\")` will correctly find the anchor element while `screen.getByText()` can still locate the chip content.\n\nI need to install the right testing dependencies, particularly `@testing-library/react@^16` for React 19 compatibility, and I'll import testing utilities directly from that library. Let me start writing the test file now, beginning with the JsonChip test cases that cover rendering with truncated text for multi-line JSON.\n\nNow I'm mapping out what each test file needs to cover—JsonChip tests for rendering and expansion, IdentityChip tests for resolved IDs and routing, and useEventExplorer tests for pagination and filtering. There's a tricky edge case in the useEventExplorer tests where the `loadMore` function guards against calling itself while already loading or when there are no more results.\n\nFor the loadMore test to work properly, I need the initial fetch to return a cursor so that `hasMore` is true and the function can actually execute. I'm also reconsidering the initial state of `hasMore`—setting it to true before the first fetch completes could trigger the IntersectionObserver prematurely, so it makes more sense to start with `hasMore=false` and update it after the first fetch returns. I'm walking through the state transitions to verify the logic works: starting with `hasMore=false` means no sentinel row initially, but once the first fetch completes with a `next_cursor`, `hasMore` becomes `true` and the IntersectionObserver can trigger for subsequent pages. The test cases confirm this behavior—when the API returns `next_cursor: null`, `hasMore` stays `false`, and when it returns a cursor value, `hasMore` becomes `true` so `loadMore()` can work. This all checks out, so I'm ready to implement it.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the `useEventExplorer` hook design around the `setFilter` function—when I call `setFilterState`, React's state update is asynchronous, but since I'm passing the new filter value directly to `fetchEvents` in the same function, the fetch gets the correct value immediately. Later when `loadMore()` runs, it'll capture the updated `filter` from the closure after React has re-rendered, so it uses the right filter value.\n\nThe dependency array on `loadMore` includes `filter`, so whenever the filter changes and the component re-renders, `loadMore` gets recreated with the new filter value—this is the correct behavior. The design checks out.\n\nNow I'm ready to start implementing. I'll install dependencies first, then write the tests, build out the components, and run validation checks. For the filter reset test specifically, I want to verify that after calling `setFilter(\"Purchase Completed\")`, the filter state updates correctly and a second fetch happens with the new filter parameter in the URL. I can check this by inspecting the mock fetch calls directly rather than parsing the URL, which is more reliable.\n\nOne thing I need to be careful about: in `useEventExplorer`, `hasMore` starts as false, so calling `loadMore` before the initial fetch completes would be blocked. But that's fine since the initial fetch is triggered by the effect, not by `loadMore`. When I test the initial fetch, the effect will fire automatically when the hook renders, so I should be able to observe that fetch call.\n\nThe tricky part is timing—since effects run asynchronously in React 18+, I need to use `waitFor` to give the fetch time to complete. Rather than waiting for the loading state to toggle, I'll wait for the events array to be populated, which is more reliable.\n\nWriting the test assertion... Writing the test setup... I'm debating whether to add the `\"use client\"` directive to the custom hook file. Since the hook uses React hooks internally, it needs to run on the client, but it's not a component itself—it'll be imported by client components anyway, so Next.js should handle it correctly without the directive. I'm writing the useEventExplorer hook that fetches event data from the API and manages the explorer state.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":498,"cache_read_input_tokens":62459,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":498},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_