{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01E8n3k2H4PTD6NyN4pzWWgN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Build passes! The ClickHouse connection errors are expected (no ClickHouse running at build time), and the build still succeeds. `/explore` is listed as a static route which means the page compiled successfully.\n\nLet me now run the full final verification:\n- Tests: all 292 pass\n- Lint: exit 0 (4 pre-existing warnings)\n- Typecheck: exit 0\n- Build: exit 0\n\nAll sprint contract criteria verified. Let me check file existence and run the HTTP check (if applicable).\n\nActually, the HTTP check requires a dev server. The sprint contract says:\n\n\n- HTTP check: GET `http://localhost:3000/explore` → response contains `Event Explorer`\n- HTTP check: GET `http://localhost:3000/explore` → response contains `data-testid=\"event-table\"` or a table element\n\nSince the page uses \"use client\", Next.js will server-render a static shell with the \"Event Explorer\" text in the initial HTML, but the table won't render until client-side hydration completes. The table element might not be visible in the raw HTML response depending on how the component is structured.\n\nFor the sprint contract checks, the first one should pass since the title is static, but the second one is problematic because the table requires client-side data fetching after mount. In Next.js App Router with \"use client\", the component gets server-rendered initially, so the HTML would likely show the empty state message instead of the table element.\n\nThe evaluator probably needs to use browser automation like Playwright to actually see the rendered page with loaded data, rather than just checking the raw server HTML. I'm seeing a contradiction between the requirements—the plan asks for an empty state message, but also expects the table element to always be present in the HTML. I think the solution is to always render the EventTable component and display a \"no events\" message inside the table body instead of replacing it entirely, so the `data-testid=\"event-table\"` attribute is guaranteed to be in the initial HTML response. Updating the explore page to always render the EventTable regardless of whether events exist, so the `data-testid=\"event-table\"` attribute is guaranteed to be present in the server-rendered HTML.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2026,"cache_read_input_tokens":94246,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2026},"output_tokens":11,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b55bde5a-8012-4aca-b30e-7084df65edbe","uuid":"b9aa8053-7d00-469c-a5a0-e6ba55f14df8"}
